<!-- Section: Startup -->
<div class="section system_manager">
  <div class="main_container">
    <div class="text bridge_description">
      <div class="subject">
        <p><strong>Initial Calibration</strong></p><br>
      </div>
      <p>This was my first real attempt at creating a class populated with methods in Ruby. I started by organizing all of my variables within the initialize method, followed by a stylish boot-up screen.</p><br>
      <p>This project really helped solidify my love of creating an immersive experience for the user. The elipses and <code>sleep</code> pauses give the sense that there's a lot happening behind the scenes as ship's systems come online.</p><br>
    </div>
    <div class="img_container">
      <%= image_tag("starship_initialize.png", :class => "starship initialize code") %>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Section: Main Menu -->
<div class="section system_manager">
  <div class="main_container">
    <div class="img_container">
      <%= image_tag("starship_setstatus.png", :class => "starship setstatus code") %>
      <%= image_tag("starship_mainmenu.png", :class => "starship mainmenu code") %>
    </div>
    <div class="text bridge_description">
      <div class="subject">
        <p><strong>Main Menu</strong></p><br>
      </div>
      <p>After the calibration the user sets up the name of the ship and the captain. The program calls the <code>status</code> method and feeds it the name variables to display at the top of the menu.</p><br>
      <p>Similarly as above, the screen is written line at a time with intricately spaced text. However, unlike the later programs, this one checks the status of the variables set in the <code>initialize</code> method and displays the corresponding message according to a conditional statement.</p><br>
      <p>At the end it calls the <code>select</code> method which asks for the user input. The user simply types in the name of the system they want to interact with.</p><br>
      <p><code>@phasers, @photons, </code>and <code>@shields</code> are simple boolean statements which the user can set to true or false.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Section: Alerts -->
<div class="section system_manager">
  <div class="main_container">
    <div class="text bridge_description">
      <div class="subject">
        <p><strong>Alerts</strong></p><br>
      </div>
      <p>The first bit of tricky code is the alert system. Instead of immediately changing the menu like with the booleans, this opens a second prompt asking the user what alert status they wish to set.</p><br>

      <p>The user has to type in the full alert status. Nearly all of the user input is put through the <code>.downcase</code> method in order to deal with any capitalization discrepancies. The <code>alerts</code> array is therefore all lowercase, while the prompt is capitalized. In this way I could not simply call the <code>alerts</code> array and display it as a string with a <code>.join</code> method.</p><br>
      <p>When the user picks an alert status the program calls the main menu again and replaces the top text with the new alert status</p><br>
      <p>The <code>@alert</code> variable is updated from a blank array to its new value and displayed accordingly.</p>
